{"id":"2012.03542","submitter":"Ian Watson","authors":"Jason Sang Hun Lee, Inkyu Park, Ian James Watson, Seungjin Yang","title":"Zero-Permutation Jet-Parton Assignment using a Self-Attention Network","comments":"Code available from https://github.com/CPLUOS/SaJa","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"hep-ex hep-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  In high-energy particle physics events, it can be advantageous to find the\njets associated with the decays of intermediate states, for example, the three\njets produced by the hadronic decay of the top quark. Typically, a\ngoodness-of-association measure, such as a $\\chi^2$ related to the mass of the\nassociated jets, is constructed, and the best jet combination is found by\noptimizing this measure. As this process suffers from a combinatorial explosion\nwith the number of jets, the number of permutations is limited by using only\nthe $n$ highest $p_T$ jets. The self-attention block is a neural network unit\nused for the neural machine translation problem, which can highlight\nrelationships between any number of inputs in a single iteration without\npermutations. In this paper, we introduce the Self-Attention for Jet Assignment\n(SaJa) network. SaJa can take any number of jets for input and outputs\nprobabilities of jet-parton assignment for all jets in a single step. We apply\nSaJa to find jet-parton assignments of fully-hadronic $t\\bar{t}$ events to\nevaluate the performance. We show that SaJa achieves better performance than a\nlikelihood-based approach.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 7 Dec 2020 09:13:12 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 9 Dec 2020 08:00:18 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Thu, 28 Apr 2022 07:32:31 GMT"},{"version":"v4","created":"Fri, 31 Mar 2023 07:34:28 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-04-03"}
